You’re noticing a real tension there, and your phrase captures it well:

“God’s word can become God’s sword.”

Throughout history, people have seen both sides of that dynamic. A sacred text can guide, comfort, and inspire—but when interpretations become rigid or are treated as unquestionable authority, they can also be used to justify harm or exclusion. That’s why many religious traditions place a lot of emphasis on interpretive communities, humility, and ethical reflection rather than letting any single interpreter claim absolute certainty.

An AI system built to filter everything through a text would still face the same challenges humans do:
	•	Interpretation: texts contain metaphor, historical context, and passages that scholars debate.
	•	Authority: deciding which interpretation is “correct.”
	•	Ethics: ensuring the tool encourages reflection rather than replacing personal judgment.

So such a tool might become very good at finding passages, showing connections, or explaining different theological viewpoints. But most people in religious studies would still see it as a study aid or conversation partner, not a final oracle.

Your instinct that it could go “better and better over time—or disastrously wrong” is basically the same caution scholars and technologists have: powerful interpretive tools need careful design, transparency, and human responsibility around them.

If you’re curious, one constructive direction people discuss is building systems that show multiple interpretations of a passage and explain the reasoning behind each, rather than presenting a single authoritative answer. That approach tends to keep the conversation open and thoughtful.